Graphical abstract The charge transfer reversal strategy was developed to fabricate nitrogen-doped carbon nanobox encapsulating a Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterojunction as an efficient and robust bi-functional oxygen electrocatalyst. The interaction between metal and support is critical in oxygen catalysis as it governs the charge transfer between these two entities, influences the electronic structures of the supported metal, affects the adsorption energies of reaction intermediates, and ultimately impacts the catalytic performance. In this study, we discovered a unique charge transfer reversal phenomenon in a metal/carbon nanohybrid system. Specifically, electrons were transferred from the metal-based species to N-doped carbon, while the carbon support reciprocally donated electrons to the metal domain upon the introduction of nickel. This led to the exceptional electrocatalytic performances of the resulting Ni-Fe/Mo2C@nitrogen-doped carbon catalyst, with a half-wave potential of 0.91 V towards oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) and a low overpotential of 290 mV at 10 mA cm−2 towards oxygen evolution reaction (OER) under alkaline conditions. Additionally, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@carbon heterojunction catalyst demonstrated high specific capacity (794 mA h gZn −1) and excellent cycling stability (200 h) in a Zn-air battery. Theoretical calculations revealed that Mo2C effectively inhibited charge transfer from Fe to the support, while secondary doping of Ni induced a charge transfer reversal, resulting in electron accumulation in the Fe-Ni alloy region. This local electronic structure modulation significantly reduced energy barriers in the oxygen catalysis process, enhancing the catalytic efficiency of both ORR and OER. Consequently, our findings underscore the potential of manipulating charge transfer reversal between the metal and support as a promising strategy for developing highly-active and durable bi-functional oxygen electrodes. Keywords Metal-support interaction Charge transfer reversal Oxygen reduction reaction Oxygen evolution reaction Zinc-air battery 1 Introduction Zinc-air batteries (ZABs) hold significant potential as a solution for meeting future energy demands in electric vehicles and energy-intensive devices owing to their environmentally friendly characteristics, high theoretical energy output, safety features, and cost-effectiveness. However, the sluggish kinetics of the oxygen reduction/evolution reactions (ORR/OER) occurring at the oxygen electrode present challenges that hinder the widespread adoption of ZABs [1,2]. Although noble metal electrocatalysts, including platinum (Pt), ruthenium dioxide (RuO2), and iridium dioxide (IrO2), have shown favorable activity for the ORR and OER, their practical application in ZABs is constrained by factors such as high cost, limited availability, poor stability, and single-functionality [3]. Therefore, the advancement of high-efficiency non-noble reversible oxygen catalysts holds paramount significance in expediting the practical realization of ZABs [4,5]. Transition metal-based catalysts are highly regarded as superior alternatives to noble metal materials, primarily due to their cost-effectiveness, abundant elemental availability, and versatile oxidation states, along with their distinctive physicochemical properties [6,7]. Notably, recent investigations have unveiled the remarkable potential of incorporating iron-based metal nanoparticles within carbon-based matrices [8]. This integration capitalizes on the robust interaction between the metal species and the supporting matrix, enabling efficient charge transfer. As a result, the electronic structure of the electrocatalyst undergoes optimization, culminating in heightened electrocatalytic efficiency and enhanced stability. For instance, Sun et al. have proficiently orchestrated a nanoarchitectural configuration, characterized by the precise incorporation of a unique jellyfish-mimetic N-doped carbon (NDC) scaffold enshrouding catalytically active Fe nanoparticles. Empirical investigations and theoretical analyses corroborated the autonomous migration of electrons from the Fe moieties towards the N-doped graphitic carbon component at the discernible heterojunction interface. Evidently, this intrinsically governed electron redistribution imparts a discernible acceleration to the overarching electron transference process, propelling it adeptly from the electrode to the reactive molecular species [9]. However, recent investigations have confirmed the critical role played by electron-enriched metal sites in optimizing the adsorption/desorption energy barriers of oxygen reaction intermediates and expediting efficient ORR pathways [10]. Consequently, the strategic manipulation of electronic characteristics germane to the Fe sites, with the intention of augmenting charge density proximate to the metallic core, emerges as a pivotal consideration. This, in turn, underscores the imperative to meticulously optimize the energy barriers governing the adsorption and desorption dynamics of intermediates involved in oxygen reactions, culminating in the construction of exceptionally proficient ORR catalysts [11]. Transition metal carbides have garnered recognition for their remarkable attributes, encompassing corrosion resistance, high mechanical strength, and exceptional stability [12]. Among these carbides, Mo2C material has surfaced as notable contender to platinum (Pt) due to its closely analogous d-band electronic structure [13]. Recently, Liu and colleagues unveiled a conspicuous electron-donating effect attributed to the Mo2C component within the NDC matrix. Consequently, through the deliberate integration of the Mo2C phase with Fe nanoparticles, a promising avenue emerges for impeding the migration of electrons from the Fe sites to the NDC skeleton. This orchestrated configuration, in turn, engenders an electron-enriched center, thereby fostering a conducive milieu for electrocatalytic reactions [14]. Conversely, the introduction of electron-withdrawing moieties in proximity to the Fe sites, such as the selective incorporation of Ni atoms with higher electronegativity into Fe-based alloy materials, has also exhibited potential in creating Fe catalytic centers endowed with negative charges to sustain efficient ORR processes [15]. However, while these strategies offer potential for modulating the electron structures of Fe active sites, it is imperative to emphasize that achieving the envisioned catalyst design is a nontrivial endeavor, necessitating the development of innovative material synthesis methodologies. Herein, we have achieved successful design and synthesis of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst by incorporating Mo2C phase and Ni constituents into a nitrogen-doped carbon framework that encapsulates Fe nanoparticles. Experimental and theoretical calculations revealed that the incorporation of Ni dopants could precisely control the electronic structure of the catalyst. This deliberate modulation contributed to a notable localized charge reversal, which significantly enhanced the conductivity of the nanohybrid catalyst and reduced the adsorption–desorption energies of reaction intermediates. Consistent with expectations, the designed catalyst exhibited outstanding electrocatalytic performance in both ORR and OER with an appreciable half-wave potential of 0.91 V and a remarkably minimal operating potential of 1.52 V at 10 mA cm−2. Therefore, these results solidly validate the accuracy and feasibility of the proposed design of this efficient bifunctional electrocatalyst. 2 Experimental 2.1 Preparations of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe nanocubes 20 mg of ferric nitrate nonahydrate and 654.5 mg of zinc nitrate hexahydrate were completely dispersed in 20 mL of ultrapure water, supplemented with 10 mg of hexadecyltrimethylammonium bromide. Subsequently, this resulting solution was swiftly introduced into a 140 mL of aqueous solution containing 9.08 g of 2-methylimidazole. Following a 30-minute stirring period at ambient temperature, the solution was subjected to heating in a water bath for a duration of 1 h. The resultant precipitates were isolated by means of a centrifuge, undergoing five consecutive washes with ultrapure water and absolute ethanol, and subsequently dried at 50 °C under vacuum conditions for 24 h. 2.2 Preparations of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo An aqueous solution was prepared by adding 100 mg of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe precursor to 12 mL of ultrapure water. Subsequently, the solution underwent the sequential addition of 200 mg of Pluronic F-127, 6 mL of ethanol, 750 μL of 1,3,5-trimethylbenzene, 10 mg of ammonium molybdate, and 25 mg of dopamine, all under the influence of magnetic stirring. Following a 30-minute stirring duration, the system was supplemented with 750 μL of NH3·H2O, initiating the polymerization of dopamine to form polydopamine (PDA). This polymerization took place under continuous stirring conditions at ambient temperature for a duration of 2 h. The resulting product was harvested using a centrifuge, subjected to a thorough washing process involving ultrapure water and absolute ethanol for a total of five cycles, and subsequently subjected to vacuum drying at a temperature of 50 °C for a period of 24 h. 2.3 Preparations of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni nanocube In a typical procedure, a total of 65.4 mg of zinc nitrate hexahydrate, 5 mg of ferric nitrate nonahydrate, and 10 mg of nickel nitrate hexahydrate were completely dispersed in 40 mL of methanol. Simultaneously, 100 mg of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo and 500 mg of 2-methylimidazole were dispersed in 80 mL of methanol. The resulting mixture was allowed to undergo a 24-hour aging process, following which the resulting product was isolated and subjected to a thorough methanol wash. Subsequently, it was dried at a temperature of 55 °C for a duration of 12 h. The preparation method employed for ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe mirrored that of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni, with the exception that Ni source was omitted from the process. 2.4 Preparations of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni 65.4 mg of zinc nitrate hexahydrate, 5 mg of ferric nitrate nonahydrate, and 10 mg of nickel nitrate hexahydrate were dispersed in 40 mL of methanol. Subsequently, a combination of 100 mg of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe and 500 mg of 2-methylimidazole dispersed in 80 mL of methanol was introduced. The resulting mixture was allowed to undergo a 24-hour incubation period, following which the product was subjected to centrifugation twice using methanol as the rinsing solvent. Finally, the obtained material was dried at a temperature of 55 °C for a duration of 24 h. 2.5 Preparations of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst A porcelain boat was loaded with 0.1 g of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni, which were subsequently positioned at the central region of a tube furnace (Anhui CHEMN Instrument Co., Ltd., TFH-1200–60-440-N). The pyrolysis procedure was carried out by subjecting the samples to 600 °C for 1 h, followed by a gradual increase to 920 °C for 2 h (3 °C min−1, N2). The fabrication of reference samples, including Fe/Mo2C@NDC, Fe@NDC, and Fe-Ni@NDC, necessitated the use of corresponding precursors, namely ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe, ZIF-8-Zn/Fe nanocube, and ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni. The subsequent calcination process was executed in congruence with the above procedures. The Supplementary Data present a detailed description of the materials employed in this study, encompassing their structural characterizations, electrochemical evaluations, and computational methodologies. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Density functional theory (DFT) calculation The modulation of electronic structures for the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC model was investigated using DFT calculations. Initially, three optimized structures were proposed for Fe@NDC, Fe/Mo2C@NDC and Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC, as demonstrated in Fig. 1 (a–c). To examine the possible electron redistribution, charge density difference analysis was conducted, and the findings were presented in Fig. 1(d–f). It is evident that the incorporation of Fe into the NDC matrix leads to an interface charge transfer from the metal to the carrier, resulting in a loss of 2.07 electrons by Fe and the acquisition of a positive charge. In the Fe/Mo2C@NDC system, the electron-donating effect of Mo2C limits the charge transfer, with Fe only losing 0.26 electrons while Mo2C loses 3.4 electrons. This indicates that the introduction of Mo2C suppresses the charge transfer from the Fe region to the carbon layer. Upon the introduction of slightly more electronegative Ni, the charge transfer from the metal phase to the carbon framework is completely reversed, resulting in a gain of 0.17 electrons by the Fe-Ni alloy. This reversal of charge transfer leads to a greater accumulation of electrons in the alloy region, which may effectively tune the electronic structures of the developed material and contribute to the enhanced ORR-OER activities of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC material [16,17]. 3.2 Preparation and structural characterization of electrocatalyst Inspired by the above DFT results, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst was designed, and the synthetic strategy is depicted in Fig. 1(g). Initially, ZIF-8-Zn/Fe nanocubes were synthesized using a simple solution-phase method. The obtained nanocubes then underwent a series of sequential reaction steps including PDA-Mo coating, the introduction of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni layer, and final high-temperature calcination. These successive reactions led to the formation of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC nanohybrids. Structural characterization for the obtained ZIF-8-Zn/Fe material was conducted using X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis, which revealed a close resemblance to the ZIF-8 structure, indicating their similar crystallographic arrangements (Fig. S1a). Elemental analysis using energy-dispersive spectroscopy (EDS) proves the presence of carbon, nitrogen, zinc, and iron elements, with iron being successfully incorporated as a trace dopant (Fig. S1b). Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) images reveal the formation of monodisperse ZIF-8-Zn/Fe nanocubes with an estimated side length of approximately 150 nm (Fig. S1c and d). The cubic morphology of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe nanocubes serves as a template throughout the morphological evolution of the catalyst. The chemical composition of dopamine, characterized by multiple amino and catechol groups, facilitates the formation of a polymer coating. The catechol moiety, known for its strong affinity towards metal ions, acted as an effective ligand for metal ion coordination [18]. By utilizing these inherent properties, the polymerization process involves the incorporation of a molybdenum source, resulting in the entrapment of molybdenum ions by PDA and the formation of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo core–shell nanostructures. The successful incorporation of the PDA-metal layer is visually observed through a color transformation of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe material from light yellow to gray in the case of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo (Fig. S2). This color change may be attributed to the inherent characteristics of melanin derived from polydopamine. Although these compositional changes are not evident in XRD analysis (Fig. S3a), the EDS spectrum confirms the presence of the Mo signal, providing evidence of its successful incorporation (Fig. S3b). Importantly, the cubic shape of the material is preserved, indicating its structural integrity (Fig. S3c and d). Subsequently, an epitaxial growth strategy was employed to introduce an additional outer shell layer composed of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni onto the surface of ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo. The resultant product evinces minimal alterations in both morphology and overall structure (Fig. S4a–c), substantiating the anticipated conformal coating process [19]. This is further corroborated by EDS mapping, which confirms the successful integration of the outermost ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni layer (Fig. S4d). Significantly, in the subsequent stages of thermal decomposition, iron and nickel participate in the amalgamation process, ultimately resulting in the formation of the Fe-Ni alloy. Concurrently, molybdenum undergoes the anticipated conversion into the Mo2C phase. Moreover, the PDA layer and the ligand undergo a transformative process, leading to the generation of the NDC framework [1]. The Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC electrocatalyst was obtained through the subsequent calcination step of the ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni precursor. The XRD analysis in Fig. 2 (a) reveals characteristic peaks at around 26° assigned to the (002) planes of graphitic-carbon, along with additional peaks attributed to hexagonal-phase Mo2C (ICDD No. 01–072-1683) and Fe-Ni alloy (Ni: ICDD 03–065-0380; Fe: ICDD 03–065-4150). The formation of Mo2C may result from the interaction between Mo ions and the ligand/PDA molecule at elevated temperatures, while the generation of Fe-Ni nanoalloys can be attributed to the reduction of metal ions during calcination [20]. Notably, meticulous scrutiny exposes a notable phenomenon: the peak positions of the Fe-Ni alloy exhibit a subtle downward shift in diffraction angles when compared to the corresponding nickel reflections. Conversely, upon comparison with the diffraction patterns of metallic iron, a reversed scenario becomes apparent. This phenomenon can be attributed to the slight disparity in atomic radii between nickel (1.24 Å) and iron (1.26 Å) [21]. Consequently, the amalgamation of iron and nickel within the alloy framework triggers either a contraction of the crystalline lattice of iron or a minor expansion of the nickel lattice. These effects collectively contribute to the observed angular deviation. The presence of these two distinct phases within the confined space of nanocubes signifies the successful incorporation of the desired Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterostructure into the derived carbon framework. The strong diffraction peaks observed indicate excellent crystallinity of the electrocatalyst, promoting efficient charge transfer during electrocatalytic processes [22]. Furthermore, no impurity peaks can be detected. The molar ratio of Fe: Ni: Mo in the obtained catalyst is calculated to be about 2.7: 1: 1.7 by inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectroscopy. Additionally, the Raman spectrum in the 1000–2000 cm−1 range exhibits two prominent signals at approximately 1360 and 1590 cm−1, attributable to the D and G bands, respectively. The ratio of I D/I G, which decreases with increasing graphitization degree, is known to indicate the degree of graphitization [23]. The resulted Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC sample exhibits an I D/I G value of 0.905 (Fig. S5a), suggesting a higher degree of graphitization and enhanced electron transfer behavior. The elemental and compositional analysis of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC nanoboxes was conducted using X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS). In the Zn 2p spectral range, discernible signals corresponding to Zn species are notably absent. This observation implies the thorough vaporization of the Zn element from the precursor during the elevated temperature calcination of 920 °C (Fig. S6), thereby facilitating the creation of a favorable pore structure in the resultant catalyst [24]. The C 1s spectra of the sample display four deconvoluted peaks at 284.8, 286.2, 287.2, and 288.6 eV attributable to graphitic C–C, C–O, C = N, and C = O groups, respectively (Fig. 2b) [25]. The presence of C = N groups confirms the efficient doping of nitrogen atoms into the carbon skeleton, providing strong evidence for the formation of nitrogen-doped carbon. As depicted in Fig. 2(c), the N 1s segment, classified into five nitrogen species, shows peaks at 396.6, 398.5, 399.4, 401.2, and 403.7 eV, corresponding to Mo-N, pyridinic N, metal-N, pyrrolic N, and graphitic N, respectively [26]. The Mo 3p peaks, located at 394.4 eV, are due to the partial overlap with the peak position of N 1s [27]. Evidently, the integration of nitrogen atoms into the catalyst matrix is accompanied by the manifestation of a diverse array of chemical environments. Notably, the nitrogen configuration encompasses four predominant primary species, namely pyridinic-N, metal-N, pyrrolic-N, and graphitic-N, collectively constituting substantial proportions of the nitrogen content [28]. Significantly, nitrogen atoms coordinated with metal entities have demonstrated pronounced adsorption affinities towards oxygen molecules, thereby expediting the reduction of intermediate species and consequentially augmenting ORR efficacy [29–31]. Conversely, the coexistence of pyridinic-N, pyrrolic-N, and graphitic-N moieties plays a pivotal role in enhancing electronic conductivity within the matrix. Consequently, the incorporation of diverse nitrogen-doping strategies synergistically heightens catalytic performance through their cumulative effects [32]. The Fe 2p high-resolution spectrum, shown in Fig. 2(d), reveals five fit peaks, ascribed to metallic Fe, Fe–N, Fe2+, Fe3+ and shakeup satellite peaks at 707.6 and 720.2 eV, 709.0 and 722.0 eV, 711.1 and 724.4 eV, 713.7 and 727.7 eV, as well as 716.7 and 731.2 eV, respectively [33,34]. In Fig. 2(e), the signals observed in the XPS spectrum of Ni 2p are fitted, revealing distinct binding energies associated with various nickel species. Specifically, metallic nickel is identified at binding energies of 854.0 and 871.3 eV, while Ni–N interactions are detected at 855.0 and 872.6 eV. Ni2+ species can be observed at binding energies of 856.9 and 875.0 eV. Additionally, a shakeup satellite peak is found at binding energies of 862.0 and 879.2 eV [35–37]. The presence of metallic signals for iron and nickel further confirms the formation of alloy materials. Moreover, the emergence of Fe–N and Ni–N moieties provides additional evidence for the production of metal-nitrogen structures, consistent with the above findings [38]. The high-resolution Mo 3d XPS spectrum of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC in Fig. 2(f) can be indexed to Mo2+ (228.3 and 231.6 eV), Mo3+ (228.9 and 232.5 eV), Mo4+ (229.8 and 234.4 eV), and Mo6+ (233.0 and 235.6 eV) [39]. It is worth noting that previous reports have identified Mo4+ and Mo6+ species in the Mo 3d region as oxidation products of MoO2 and MoO3, respectively, upon exposure to air. Based on the above analysis, it can be inferred that the Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterostructure has been successfully anchored within the derived nitrogen-doped carbon substrate, in line with XRD and Raman findings. The surface morphology and crystal structure of the fabricated catalysts were systematically examined using SEM, transmission electron microscopy (TEM), and TEM-EDS mapping. SEM images displayed in Fig. 2(g and h) unveil a plethora of well-dispersed nanocubes exhibiting a rough surface morphology in the obtained Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC sample, which can be attributed to the high-temperature pyrolysis process. Importantly, the overall morphology of the catalyst remains largely unchanged, albeit with a slight reduction in size (from 280 to 200 nm). The reduction in size of this magnitude is likely attributed to the escape of various volatile substances during the high-temperature pyrolysis process [2]. Upon meticulous observation, it becomes discernible that the surface of the nanocubes harbors certain one-dimensional nanostructures. TEM analysis further elucidates a well-defined hollow nanocube structure with a thin and porous shell layer for Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC (Fig. 2i), facilitating the efficient transfer of reaction intermediates and providing increased active sites. Additionally, in-situ growth of carbon nanotubes on the nanobox surface is further observed. The formation of these nanotubes should follow the metal-catalyzed growth mechanism, which may contribute to promoting enhanced electron transport and an enlarged electrochemically active area [21]. Notably, these carbon nanotubes encapsulate metal particles (as indicated in Fig. 2i), suggesting the potential catalytic growths of carbon tubes facilitated by the presence of adjacent Fe-Ni nanoparticles. High-resolution TEM imaging (Fig. 2j–l) reveals distinct lattice fringes with lattice spacings of 0.228 and 0.180 nm, assigned to the (121) crystal plane of Mo2C and the (200) crystal plane of Fe-Ni alloy, respectively. These observations align with the findings from the selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern, as illustrated in the inset of Fig. 2(j). These findings confirm the successful incorporation of Fe-Ni alloy and Mo2C within the carbon framework. Furthermore, an interplanar spacing of approximately 0.34 nm, attributable to the (002) crystal plane of graphite carbon, indicates a higher degree of graphitization in the derived carbon matrix. The extensively graphitized carbon structure offers dual benefits to the active site, including a substantial enhancement in conductivity and effective safeguarding and stabilization of the embedded nanoparticles, thus facilitating efficient and stable charge transfer [40,41]. Moreover, TEM-EDS element mapping images (Fig. 2m) demonstrate the uniform dispersion of Fe-Ni alloy and Mo2C throughout the entire carbon framework, as evidenced by strong signals of C and N elements along with Fe, Ni, and Mo element signals, clearly outlining the geometric contour of the cubic box. Therefore, these observations confirm the successful coupling between Fe-Ni alloy and Mo2C in the carbon skeleton, suggesting its promising electrocatalytic ORR-OER performances. 3.3 Evaluation of ORR performances The ORR performances of the synthesized catalysts were evaluated using a conventional three-electrode setup in a potassium hydroxide solution (0.1 M) [22]. A series of designed samples were synthesized to investigate the influential factors. Specifically, the Fe@NDC product was obtained by direct calcination of the ZIF-8-Zn/Fe nanocube (Fig. S7), allowing us to examine the impact of the Fe component on electrocatalytic activity. In contrast to the synthesis method used in ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni, this study involved synthesizing the ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@PDA-Mo@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe precursor, followed by subsequent pyrolysis treatment, which resulted in the formation of the Fe/Mo2C@NDC, as shown in Fig. S8, thus demonstrating the influence of Ni introduction on electrocatalytic efficiency. To establish the intrinsic relationship between the Mo2C component and ORR performance, ZIF-8-Zn/Fe@ZIF-8-Zn/Fe/Ni was synthesized without the middle PDA-Mo layer. The resulting material underwent high-temperature pyrolysis, thereby contributing to the fabrication of the Fe-Ni@NDC sample (Fig. S9). The electrocatalytic performances of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC, Fe/Mo2C@NDC, Fe@NDC and Fe-Ni@NDC for the ORR were initially investigated using cyclic voltammetry (CV) plots in N2– and O2-saturated potassium hydroxide solutions. Fig. 3 (a) demonstrates the presence of a cathodic peak in the O2-saturated electrolyte, while no redox peak is observed in the nitrogen-saturated electrolyte [42,43]. Remarkably, Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC exhibits a superior cathodic signal at 0.925 V (vs. RHE) compared to Fe/Mo2C@NDC (0.918 V), Fe@NDC (0.874 V), and Fe-Ni@NDC (0.745 V), indicating its excellent ORR activity. To further evaluate the ORR performances of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC product, linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) experiments were conducted using a rotating disk electrode (1600 r min−1) in the oxygen-saturated electrolyte (Fig. 3b) [44]. Obviously, Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC demonstrates the highest ORR activity among all the catalysts, displaying the most positive initial potential (E onset = 1.034 V) and half-wave potential (E 1/2 = 0.91 V), as well as the highest diffusion-limited current density (j L = 5.87 mA cm−2). These values surpass those of Fe/Mo2C@NDC (E onset = 1.014 V; E 1/2 = 0.90 V; j L = 5.49 mA cm−2), Fe@NDC (E onset = 1.011 V; E 1/2 = 0.883 V; j L = 5.38 mA cm−2), Fe-Ni@NDC (E onset = 0.975 V; E 1/2 = 0.84 V; j L = 3.99 mA cm−2), Pt/C catalysts (E onset = 1.025 V; E 1/2 = 0.835 V; j L = 5.30 mA cm−2), and other recently reported ORR catalysts (Table S1). Interestingly, Fe@NDC displays certain ORR performance, suggesting the potential involvement of the Fe component as the primary active site. Upon introducing the Mo2C phase, the resulting Fe/Mo2C@NDC electrocatalyst exhibits a slight performance improvement, further supporting the role of the Fe component as the active site and the effective control of the electronic structure of the electrocatalyst by the Mo2C phase. Introducing Ni into the Fe/Mo2C@NDC system yields the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst, displaying the best ORR efficiency, which can be attributed to the expected charge redistribution induced by nickel. Conversely, Fe-Ni@NDC, lacking the Mo2C component, exhibits the lowest electrocatalytic performance, highlighting the synergistic catalytic effect of Mo2C. Inhibition investigations were conducted through the immersion of the catalyst in a potassium thiocyanate (KSCN) solution. This approach was selected due to the recognized strong coordination propensity of SCN− ions with iron species, consequently impeding their electrocatalytic prowess [4]. Illustrated in Fig. S10, the introduction of KSCN into the electrolyte leads to a marked decline in the ORR performance of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst, thereby underscoring the vital role of the metal catalytic centers as pivotal active sites within this system. The ORR kinetics of various electrocatalysts were investigated by analyzing their Tafel slopes [45,46]. Among the tested catalysts, Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC exhibits the most favorable ORR kinetics, with a significantly lower Tafel slope of 89 mV dec−1 (Fig. 3c), implying its superb electrocatalytic kinetics. Furthermore, the electron transfer number of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC is determined (Fig. 3d) and calculated to be approximately 4, as per eq. (1) in the Supplementary Materials, implying a predominant four-electron process in the ORR catalyzed by Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC [47]. Additionally, the negligible yield of hydrogen peroxide based on eq. (2) suggests that the primary products of the ORR process are OH− species [48]. In assessing catalyst performance and practical application, methanol resistance and long-term durability are critical parameters. Fig. S11(a) demonstrates the remarkable methanol tolerance and sustained current density of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC electrocatalyst in the presence of 1 mL of methanol, surpassing that of the Pt-based sample [49]. The chronoamperometric measurements conducted over a continuous 24-hour operation demonstrate the outstanding durability for the developed Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst in its ORR activity, exhibiting only a marginal decrease of 4.3% [50]. This decrease is significantly lower when compared to the commercial nobel-metal electrocatalyst, which experiences a substantial decrease of 39.1%, as illustrated in Fig. S11(b). Fig. S11(c) affords the polarization curves of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC sample after undergoing stability testing, indicating no significant loss in the values of j L and E 1/2. Furthermore, XPS and HR-TEM results demonstrate that the designed catalyst retained its initial compositions and structures (Fig. S11d–h). Taken together, these findings highlight Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC as a promising candidate for cathode catalyst applications in ZABs, exhibiting exceptional performance in terms of stability, activity, and selectivity towards the ORR. 3.4 Evaluation of OER performances The Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC sample demonstrates superior OER performance, which is of significant importance for advancing high-performance rechargeable ZABs [51,52]. As illustrated in Fig. 3(e), the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC electrode yields decent catalytic efficiency in terms of a minimal overpotential 290 mV at 10 mA cm−2. In contrast, the Fe/Mo2C@NDC catalysts exhibit poor activities, as evidenced by the high overpotential (η 10 = 432 mV) observed during OER. Moreover, the Fe@NDC and Fe-Ni@NDC samples demonstrate insignificant OER performances. Moreover, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC material exhibits superior performance compared to the commercial noble metal RuO2 catalyst (η 10 = 310 mV) and previously reported catalysts based on non-noble metals (Table S1). The outstanding OER efficiency observed in Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC can be attributed to the same underlying factors that contribute to its superior ORR performance. Additionally, the electrochemical dynamics of the electrocatalyst in the OER process were evaluated using the Tafel plot [53,54]. Among the tested electrocatalysts, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC electrode affords the smallest Tafel slope of 70 mV dec−1 (Fig. 3f). This indicates that the Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterojunction embedded in the carbon nanobox facilitates rapid electron transfer, as further supported by the corresponding results obtained from electrochemical impedance spectroscopy techniques (Fig. 3g). The representative features of the Nyquist plot are the semi-arc formed at low frequencies, whose diameter is a measure for the charge-transfer resistance. The smallest semi-arc of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC means its highest charge-transfer, which may be ascribed to its promoted electronic conductivity [3]. Turnover frequency (TOF) measurements confirm that Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC product exhibits the first-rank TOF value (8.89 s−1), surpassing those of Fe/Mo2C@NDC (0.14 s−1), Fe@NDC (0.07 s−1), and Fe-Ni@NDC (0.03 s−1), which aligns with the observed order of overpotential (Fig. S12) [55]. Additionally, the catalytic ability of the designed electrocatalyst is closely associated with the presence of abundant catalytic centers. To evaluate the electrochemically active surface area of the samples, their double-layer capacitance (C dl) was measured [56]. As shown in Fig. S13, Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC affords a superb C dl value of 1.24 mF cm−2. This indicates that the Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterojunction can provide abundant active sites, promoting the acceleration of the electrocatalytic reaction. The Faradaic efficiency of the generated O2 was determined, and the resulting Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst demonstrates an efficiency of nearly 99%, indicating that the excellent performance is attributed to water oxidation rather than the self-oxidation of the catalyst (Fig. S14) [57,58]. The durability of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst during OER was assessed through chronoamperometric measurements, revealing a minimal 1.1% increase in driving voltage following 24 h of uninterrupted operations (Fig. 3h). This result attests to its commendable OER stability. Notably, this stability is also corroborated by the near-identical OER LSV profiles recorded prior to and post 24-hour operation, as depicted in Fig. S15. XRD, SEM, TEM and XPS tests were conducted to examine any changes in phase, morphology, and composition of the sample post-testing, demonstrating that the catalyst maintained its original state without undergoing any phase transition, and thus highlighting its appreciable stability (Fig. S16). Furthermore, the evaluation index of reversible oxygen catalytic activity, ΔE (between E j = 10 and E 1/2) [59], is calculated for the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst, indicating the minimum ΔE value of 0.61 V (Fig. 3i), significantly better than the values obtained for the comparison samples, the RuO2-Pt/C coupling and other documented bi-functional electrocatalysts (Table S1). 3.5 Mechanism analysis for enhanced electrochemical performance Upon computational analysis (Fig. 4 a–c), the d-band center of Fe@NDC registers at −0.88 eV, while in the case of Fe/Mo2C@NDC, the d-band center of Fe is measured at −1.03 eV. For Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC, the d-band centers of Fe and Ni are observed at −1.24 eV and −1.50 eV, respectively. The discernible influence of elevated d-band centers, such as observed in Fe@NDC and Fe/Mo2C@NDC configurations, manifests in an excessive affinity for intermediate *OH species, thereby constraining their ORR capabilities. With the subsequent integration of nickel, the pronounced electronegativity of Ni enables electron acquisition from the Mo2C domain, subsequently elevating the Fermi energy level. This adjustment precipitates a reduction in the d-band center, thereby mitigating the *OH intermediate adsorption and, correspondingly, enhancing the ORR activity [60]. The ORR/OER reaction pathway in alkaline electrolytes involves four distinct reaction steps, primarily characterized by the adsorption and desorption mechanisms of the intermediates of *OH, *O, and *OOH. The optimized structures of these intermediates in each reaction step are depicted in Fig. 4(d) for Fe@NDC, Fe/Mo2C@NDC and Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC. In the ORR process, the rate-limiting step for both Fe@NDC and Fe/Mo2C@NDC is identified as the desorption of *OH, despite the strong interaction between the carbon carrier and Fe (Fig. 4e). This similarity in rate-limiting steps can be attributed to the consistent charge state of Fe species in both catalysts. This finding underscores the importance of modifying the charge state of iron active sites to modulate the rate-determining step of the ORR and enhance its catalytic efficiency. As expected, the introduction of Ni dopants into the Fe/Mo2C@NDC system facilitates the transformation of Fe-Ni nanoparticles within the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC sample into a negatively charged state. This state is characterized by the presence of negatively charged centers, which typically yield favorable outcomes for the ORR [61]. Moreover, the findings depicted in Fig. 4(e) illustrate that the excessive binding strength of three reaction intermediates contributes to the inadequate ORR activities observed in the Fe@NDC and Fe/Mo2C@NDC catalysts. Conversely, the negatively charged Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst effectively weakens the binding strength of intermediates, leading to a significant improvement in ORR activity, which is in line with the above findings in d-band regulation. Moreover, this modification greatly influences the rate-determining step in the ORR, with the formation of *OOH species emerging as the pivotal determining factor in the resultant Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst [62]. During the OER process, the rate-determining step for the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst and Fe/Mo2C@NDC involves the transformation from *O to *OOH, while for Fe@NDC, it can be attributed to the transformation from *OOH to O2. Moreover, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst, which demonstrates superior OER performance, exhibits the lowest reaction barrier among the studied catalysts, suggesting that the overpotential of the OER can be continuously diminished by sequentially incorporating Mo2C and nickel components (Fig. 4f). Therefore, it is worth noting that the introduction of nickel in the Ni-Fe/Mo2C@NDC catalyst leads to a favorable reversed charge transfer process, which effectively adjusts the binding strength of intermediates and improves its catalytic performance, consistent with the experimental findings. Moreover, the direction of electron flow can be further confirmed through ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy [63]. Consistent with expectations, the estimated working function (W F) of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC is 6.64 eV, which is lower than those of Fe/Mo2C@NDC and Fe@NDC (Fig. 4g). The W F of a material quantifies the energy barriers associated with electron emission from the semiconductor to the vacuum level, as well as the energy difference between the vacuum level and the Fermi level (E F). The strategic design and fabrication of heterojunctions through the integration of constituents with contrasting W F have been widely acknowledged as an effective approach to facilitate efficient interfacial electron migration, thereby facilitating an optimized rearrangement of charge carriers [64]. This phenomenon can result in advantageous adsorption energies for intermediate products, thereby promoting the acceleration of electrocatalytic ORR-OER reactions. As evident from the results depicted in Fig. 4(h), the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC sample displays a valence-band maximum (VBM) value of 0.21 eV. Notably, this VBM value is relatively lower compared to the VBM values observed for the two reference samples. This observation suggests that the exposed surfaces of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC nanocomposites possess a higher density of states around the E F, indicating a more metallic character. This observation can also be substantiated through corresponding XPS analysis. As demonstrated in Fig. 2, Fig. S7 and S8, and Table S2, it is discernible that the iron signal within Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC experiences a marginal shift towards lower binding energy when juxtaposed with analogous data from Fe/Mo2C@NDC and Fe@NDC. This shift underscores the anticipated reversal in charge transfer, attributed to the comparatively robust electronegativity of the incorporated Ni dopant. Consequently, this alteration in charge transfer dynamics optimally fine-tunes the adsorption/desorption energy barriers across various intermediates, thereby potentiating catalytic efficiency. The surface area and pore structure of the synthesized catalyst were assessed using N2 adsorption/desorption isotherms [65]. As illustrated in Fig. S17, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC material demonstrates a BET-specific surface area of 449.5 m2 g−1, complemented by a well-defined pore structure. The existence of an ample porous framework conventionally corresponds to an expanded specific surface area, thus significantly amplifying the quantum of active sites. Moreover, the existence of accessible conduits exerts a substantial influence on mass transfer during electrocatalytic processes, thereby conspicuously elevating the electrocatalytic efficacy of the catalyst [66,67]. Conversely, although the specific surface area of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC is comparatively lower in relation to Fe@NDC, Fe/Mo2C@NDC, and Fe-Ni@NDC, its proficiency in ORR and OER can be enhanced through the synergistic modulation of electronic structure facilitated by Mo2C and Ni doping. Moreover, the optimized catalyst exhibits the highest level of graphitization, which enhances the electron transport efficiency during the electrocatalytic reaction (Fig. S5). This factor also serves a vital role in promoting the overall catalytic performance of the catalyst. It is noteworthy to highlight that Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC exhibits an optimal degree of graphitization. This propensity could potentially be attributed to the presence of multiple metallic components within the material system, which facilitate the growth of graphitic carbon through catalytic mechanisms [68]. 3.6 Evaluation of ZABs performances To evaluate the applicability of the designed catalyst in practical scenarios, a primary ZABs device was fabricated using Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC product as the cathode. The schematic representation of the battery fabrication process is shown in Fig. 5 (a) and Fig. S18. For comparison purposes, a Pt-based ZABs device was also assembled. Expectedly, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC cathode yields a remarkable peak power density of 444 mW cm−2 at 400 mA cm−2 (Fig. 5b), outperforming the Pt/C-based ZABs (165.1 mW cm−2 at 309.9 mA cm−2) and other reported catalysts (Table S3). Additionally, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC-based battery exhibits a higher specific discharge capacity compared to the commercial Pt/C-based ZABs (794 mA h gZn −1 vs. 689 mA h gZn −1), as demonstrated in Fig. 5(c). The discharging/charging polarization plots displayed in Fig. 5(d) further emphasize the superiority of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC-based ZABs over the coupling of Pt/C and RuO2, with a significantly smaller charge/discharge voltage gap at the same current density. Specifically, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC cathode achieves a charge–discharge voltage of 0.75 V at 50 mA cm−2, markedly superior to the 1.37 V of the noble metal-based battery. These results highlight the outstanding ORR/OER activity of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst (Fig. 5d). Furthermore, the as-obtained Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC electrode demonstrates remarkable long-term electrochemical stability during charge–discharge processes, as demonstrated in Fig. 5(e). Under a constant current density of 10 mA cm−2, the electrode exhibits a charge–discharge voltage of below 0.89 V for both the 2-hour and 110-hour time points. Impressively, even after 200 h, the voltage remains steady at 0.93 V, highlighting the exceptional durability of this electrode. These performance metrics surpass those of the Pt/C-RuO2 cathode and the documented rechargeable ZABs (Table S4). Additionally, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC air–cathode demonstrates a high open-circuit voltage of 1.501 V (Fig. 5f), making it suitable for powering LED viewing screens or LED lights with one or two cells connected in series (Fig. 5g, h). Thus, these findings establish the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC as a durable and efficient bifunctional oxygen electrocatalyst for practical ZABs devices. The superb catalytic performance of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst is attributable to several key factors. Firstly, the sequential introduction of Mo2C and nickel doping induces a reversed charge transfer in the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC system, leading to the optimization of the electronic structure of the electrocatalyst and the reduction of reaction energy barriers during the electrocatalytic ORR/OER process [61]. Secondly, the presence of the Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterojunction interface provides a large number of active sites, thereby enhancing the overall ORR/OER performance [60]. Thirdly, the unique hollow structure of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC creates favorable spaces for catalytic activity and facilitates stable charge transfer, thereby promoting the relevant electrocatalytic processes [69]. Lastly, the graphitized framework not only enhances the conductivity of the catalyst but also provides robust protection for the active site [70]. The noteworthy bi-functional catalytic activity of Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC originates from the synergistic catalytic effect of multiple active components, highlighting the significance of their collective contribution rather than relying solely on a single component. 4 Conclusions In summary, we have successfully synthesized and characterized a nitrogen-doped carbon nanobox encapsulating a Fe-Ni/Mo2C heterojunction, which exhibits excellent catalytic performance as a bi-functional electrocatalyst for ORR and OER. The introduction of Ni dopants and Mo2C phase induces a reversed charge transfer at the metal-carrier interface, leading to a significant reduction in the energy barrier for ORR and OER, thereby enhancing the electrochemical performance. Specifically, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@NDC catalyst demonstrated a noteworthy half-wave potential of 0.91 V for ORR and a desirable overpotential of 290 mV at 10 mA cm−2 for OER. Furthermore, the assembled ZABs using this catalyst exhibit a specific capacity of 794 mA h gZn −1 and excellent cycling stability, highlighting their potential for practical applications in the field of ZABs. This study provides valuable insights into the influence of the metal-carrier interface on catalytic activity and presents a novel strategy for the design of highly efficient and durable electrocatalysts for both ORR and OER by the electronic structure regulation. coredata.dc:description: The interaction between metal and support is critical in oxygen catalysis as it governs the charge transfer between these two entities, influences the electronic structures of the supported metal, affects the adsorption energies of reaction intermediates, and ultimately impacts the catalytic performance. In this study, we discovered a unique charge transfer reversal phenomenon in a metal/carbon nanohybrid system. Specifically, electrons were transferred from the metal-based species to N-doped carbon, while the carbon support reciprocally donated electrons to the metal domain upon the introduction of nickel. This led to the exceptional electrocatalytic performances of the resulting Ni-Fe/Mo2C@nitrogen-doped carbon catalyst, with a half-wave potential of 0.91 V towards oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) and a low overpotential of 290 mV at 10 mA cm−2 towards oxygen evolution reaction (OER) under alkaline conditions. Additionally, the Fe-Ni/Mo2C@carbon heterojunction catalyst demonstrated high specific capacity (794 mA h gZn −1) and excellent cycling stability (200 h) in a Zn-air battery. Theoretical calculations revealed that Mo2C effectively inhibited charge transfer from Fe to the support, while secondary doping of Ni induced a charge transfer reversal, resulting in electron accumulation in the Fe-Ni alloy region. This local electronic structure modulation significantly reduced energy barriers in the oxygen catalysis process, enhancing the catalytic efficiency of both ORR and OER. Consequently, our findings underscore the potential of manipulating charge transfer reversal between the metal and support as a promising strategy for developing highly-active and durable bi-functional oxygen electrodes.
